comments.body:
If these are considered low enough risk to allow non priv users to mount, I don't see why SELinux should block.

allow container_t devpts_t:chr_file { open setattr };
allow container_t devpts_t:dir mounton;
allow container_t devpts_t:filesystem mount;
allow container_t proc_t:dir mounton;
allow container_t sysfs_t:filesystem remount;
allow container_t tmpfs_t:filesystem mount;
I guess the real question is why are these not labeled.

We have a devpts_t that is being mounted on?  Is this the systems /dev/pts?  
Mounting on /proc directories is probably not a concern?

[dwalsh@localhost psgo]$ sesearch -A -s container_t -p mount
allow container_domain container_file_t:filesystem { mount remount unmount };
allow container_t fusefs_t:filesystem mount; [ virt_sandbox_use_fusefs ]:True
allow svirt_sandbox_domain fusefs_t:filesystem mount; [ virt_sandbox_use_fusefs ]:True
allow svirt_sandbox_domain nfs_t:filesystem mount; [ virt_use_nfs ]:True
